INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3000','letter','1775-08-01','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','We understand here, that batteries may be constructed at the entrance of the Bay of Boston, so as to prevent the egress and regress of any ships what ever.','ltr_rhl3000.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3001','letter','1775-09-26','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','We have no late accounts from England ; but from what we have had that can be relied on, it seems almost certain, that our enemies there must shortly meet with a total overthrow.','ltr_rhl3001.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3002','letter','1775-10-22','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','Great bodies, you know, move slow, and it is as sure, that the most palpable and glorious events may be delayed, and the best causes finally lost by slow, timid, and indecisive counsels.','ltr_rhl3002.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3003','letter','1775-12-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','The proclamation, there alluded to, we have seen. It proclaims martial law through Virginia, and orders freedom to all the slaves, calling their masters rebels, &c.','ltr_rhl3003.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3004','letter','1776-06-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am informed that a certain Mr. Eustace, now in New York, but some time ago with Lord Dunmore, is acquainted with a practice that prevailed, of taking letters out of the post-office in Virginia, and carrying them to Dunmore for his perusal','ltr_rhl3004.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3005','letter','1777-04-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','My wishes are, Sir, and I think they correspond with the true interests of America, that you should quickly be possessed of a strong army ; that your powers might be such as to gratify your wishes of crushing our enemies','ltr_rhl3005.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume I., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3200','letter','1777-10-20','York','NY','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','was a good deal surprised to find you had been told that Congress had appointed General Conway a Major-General. No such appointment has been made ; nor do I believe it will','ltr_rhl3200.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3201','letter','1777-10-20','York','NY','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','General Conway has not lately been mentioned in Congress, nor has there been much talk of an Adjutant-General, since it is not certainly known whether Colonel Pickering will accept his new appointment.','ltr_rhl3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3202','letter','1778-05-16','York','NY','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','individual','','Give me leave, dear Sir, to congratulate you on the happy event of our treaty with France being so effectually concluded. Congress have ratified it on their part','ltr_rhl3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_rhl3203','letter','1778-10-05','Philadelphia','PA','US','Richard','Lee','','George','Washington','','I hope the measures you have taken will be effectual to the purpose of reenlisting the army, because it is an object of great importance','','description','ltr_rhl3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
